# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chester-stock
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A magnitude 7.9 earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 05:12 am Pacific Standard Time on Wednesday, April 18, 1906.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] With a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*), it created high-intensity shaking from Eureka on the North Coast to the Salinas Valley, an agricultural region to the south of the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Extensive fires soon broke out in San Francisco and lasted for several days.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than 3,000 people died and over 80% of the city was destroyed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The event is remembered as the deadliest earthquake in the history of the United States.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The death toll remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history and high on the list of worst American disasters, natural or man-made.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault is a continental transform fault that forms part of the tectonic boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strike-slip fault is characterized by mainly lateral motion in a dextral sense, where the western (Pacific) plate moves northward relative to the eastern (North American) plate.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This fault runs the length of California from the Salton Sea in the south to Cape Mendocino in the north, a distance of about 810 miles (1,300 km).
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The maximum observed surface displacement was about 20 feet (6 m); geodetic measurements show displacements of up to 28 feet (8.5 m).
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 earthquake preceded the development of the Richter scale.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most widely accepted estimate for the magnitude of the quake on the modern moment magnitude scale is 7.9; values from 7.7 to as high as 8.3 have been proposed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] According to findings published in the *Journal of Geophysical Research*, severe deformations in the Earth's crust took place both before and after the earthquake's impact.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accumulated strain on the faults in the system was relieved during the earthquake, which is the supposed cause of the damage along the 280-mile-long (450 km) segment of the San Andreas plate boundary.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 rupture propagated both northward and southward for a total of 296 miles (476 km).
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shaking was felt from Oregon to Los Angeles, and as far inland as central Nevada.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A strong foreshock preceded the main shock by about 20 to 25 seconds.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strong shaking of the main shock lasted about 42 seconds.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] There were decades of minor earthquakes – more than at any other time in the historical record for northern California – before the 1906 quake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For years, the epicenter of the quake was assumed to be near the town of Olema, in the Point Reyes area of Marin County, due to local earth displacement measurements.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the 1960s, a seismologist at UC Berkeley proposed that the epicenter was more likely offshore of San Francisco, to the northwest of the Golden Gate.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most recent analyses support an offshore location for the epicenter, although significant uncertainty remains.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An offshore epicenter is supported by the occurrence of a local tsunami recorded by a tide gauge at the San Francisco Presidio; the wave had an amplitude of approximately 3 inches (7.6 cm) and an approximate period of 40–45 minutes.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Analysis of triangulation data before and after the earthquake strongly suggests that the rupture along the San Andreas Fault was about 310 miles (500 km) in length, in agreement with observed intensity data.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The available seismological data support a significantly shorter rupture length, but these observations can be reconciled by allowing propagation at speeds above the S-wave velocity (supershear).
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Supershear propagation has now been recognized for many earthquakes associated with strike-slip faulting.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2019, using an old photograph and a recorded eyewitness account, researchers were able to refine the location of the hypocenter of the earthquake as offshore from San Francisco or near San Juan Bautista, confirming previous estimates.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The shaking intensity as described on the Modified Mercalli intensity scale reached XI (*Extreme*) in San Francisco and areas to the north like Santa Rosa where destruction was devastating.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most important characteristic of the shaking intensity noted in Andrew Lawson's 1908 report was the clear correlation of intensity with underlying geologic conditions.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Areas situated in sediment-filled valleys sustained stronger shaking than nearby bedrock sites, and the strongest shaking occurred in areas of former bay where soil liquefaction had occurred.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Modern seismic-zonation practice accounts for the differences in hazard posed by varying geologic conditions.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The main shock was followed by many aftershocks and some remotely triggered events.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As with the 1857 Fort Tejon earthquake, there were fewer aftershocks than would have been expected for a shock of that size.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Very few of them were located along the trace of the 1906 rupture, tending to concentrate near the ends of the rupture or on other structures away from the San Andreas Fault, such as the Hayward Fault.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The only aftershock in the first few days of near MI 5 or greater occurred near Santa Cruz at 14:28 PST on April 18, with a magnitude of about 4.9 M.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The largest aftershock happened at 01:10 PST on April 23, west of Eureka with an estimated magnitude of about 6.7 MI, with another of the same size more than three years later at 22:45 PST on October 28 near Cape Mendocino.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Remotely triggered events included an earthquake swarm in the Imperial Valley area, which culminated in an earthquake of about 6.1 MI at 16:30 PST on April 18, 1906.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another event of this type occurred at 12:31 PST on April 19, 1906, with an estimated magnitude of about 5.0 MI, and an epicenter beneath Santa Monica Bay.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Seismographs on the U.S. east coast recorded the earthquake some 19 minutes later.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some early death estimates exceeded 500.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Early death counts ranged from 375 to over 500.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] However, hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The total number of deaths is still uncertain, but various reports presented a range of 700–3,000+.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005, the city's Board of Supervisors voted unanimously in support of a resolution written by novelist James Dalessandro ("1906") and city historian Gladys Hansen ("Denial of Disaster") to recognize the figure of 3,000+ as the official total.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the deaths occurred within San Francisco, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities such as Santa Rosa and San Jose also suffered severe damage.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake and fire left long-standing and significant pressures on the development of California.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At the time of the disaster, San Francisco had been the ninth-largest city in the United States and the largest on the West Coast.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over a period of 60 years, the city had become the financial, trade, and cultural center of the West, operating the busiest port on the West Coast.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was the "gateway to the Pacific", through which growing U.S. economic and military power was projected into the Pacific and Asia.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over 80% of the city was destroyed by the earthquake and fire.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Though San Francisco rebuilt quickly, the disaster diverted trade, industry, and population growth south to Los Angeles, which during the 20th century became the largest and most important urban area in the West.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Many of the city's leading poets and writers retreated to Carmel-by-the-Sea where, as "The Barness", they established the arts colony reputation that continues today.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1908 Lawson Report, a study of the 1906 quake led and edited by Professor Andrew Lawson of the University of California, showed that the same San Andreas Fault which had caused the disaster in San Francisco ran close to Los Angeles as well.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was the first natural disaster of its magnitude to be documented by photography and motion picture footage and occurred at a time when the science of seismology was blossoming.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from San Francisco on April 23, five days after the earthquake, resident John W.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nourse described the scene to his family in Indiana: woken at quarter past five by shaking that made the house "seem like it would break all to pieces," he looked out to see a large brick building completely destroyed in seconds, with fires visible simultaneously to the right, front, and left.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Grabbing the baby's buggy, he and his wife Lena fled to Market Street, which he described as a terrible sight.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Whole blocks reduced to masses of ruins, City Hall a complete wreck.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He left his wife and baby at the mission and returned to try to save their belongings, but found the whole part of the city burning.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "In traveling over the city it looks like there is not a building but what is more or less damaged," he wrote.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A traveler passing through San Francisco ten days after the earthquake, Mrs.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Baughman of LeMars, Iowa, described a stove placed in front of every house, residents were not permitted to cook indoors, and Market Street sunken several feet in places, with one point four blocks from the Ferry five feet lower than the sidewalk and the cable car rails warped and twisted.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] She observed soldiers with blue coats throughout the begrimed crowds, groups of listless dazed men in the suburbs, and frame buildings near Valencia Street completely shattered within a radius of several blocks.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from Boulder Creek, eighty miles south of San Francisco, former journalist Mathias Forestburg described being violently awakened by the shaking, the house rocking like a boat with timbers creaking and everything thrown to the floor.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He spent the morning dismantling a cracked chimney that was balanced on three bricks.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One more aftershock would have brought it down and demolished the house.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He reported continual shaking every day and night since the earthquake, keeping the community on constant alert, and noted that all business had stopped and all who could afford to leave were going east.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most immediate firsthand account came from Lewis A.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer of San Jose, who wrote to his brother-in-law in Virginia at midnight on the day of the earthquake itself.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer had been staying at a mineral spring in the mountains the previous night; waking just before 5 AM, he was thrown against the wall at 5:15 as the shock struck while he was putting a pan of water on the stove.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Electric cars had stopped running and he hired a farmer to bring him home by buggy.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He found his house standing with only cracked plaster, but described San Jose as "in ruins.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fine business houses flat on the ground" and San Francisco as nearly all in ruins and in flames.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] His son-in-law had arrived from San Francisco reporting that Spitzer's son and his wife and baby appeared to have escaped safely, but the family could not reach them.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The streets were full of people camping in tents, some without tents, afraid to go indoors.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "I have seen many heart rending scenes in my life," he wrote, "but never any such a terrible scene as this.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Although the impact of the earthquake on San Francisco was the most famous, the earthquake also inflicted considerable damage on several other cities.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These include San Jose and Santa Rosa, the entire downtown of which was essentially destroyed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Duffy of Owensboro, Kentucky, who had been staying at the St.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rose Hotel in Santa Rosa, reported being trapped for five hours in the ruins before rescuers reached him.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He finally made his location known by poking a lath through a hole left by a falling steam pipe.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As damaging as the earthquake and its aftershocks were, the fires that burned out of control afterward were far more destructive.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It has been estimated that at least 80%, and at most over 95%, of the total destruction was the result of the subsequent fires.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Within three days, over 30 fires, that were caused by ruptured gas mains, destroyed approximately 25,000 buildings on 490 city blocks.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The fires cost an estimated $350 million at the time (equivalent to $9.1 billion in 2024).
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The *Ham and Eggs* fire, in the morning on the 18th, at Hayes and Gough Streets, in Hayes Valley, was started by a woman who lit her stove to prepare breakfast, unaware of the badly damaged chimney, destroying a 30-block area, including a college, the Hall of Records and City Hall.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the fires were started when San Francisco Fire Department firefighters, untrained in the use of dynamite, attempted to demolish buildings to create firebreaks.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The dynamited buildings often caught fire.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, who would have been responsible for coordinating firefighting efforts, had died from injuries sustained in the initial quake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In total, the fires burned for four days and nights.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the destruction in the city was attributed to the fires, since widespread practice by insurers was to indemnify San Francisco properties from fire but not from earthquake damage.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Army Signal Corps reported that he "was stopped by a fireman who told me that people in that neighborhood were firing their houses...they were told that they would not get their insurance on buildings damaged by the earthquake unless they were damaged by fire".
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One landmark building lost in the fire was the Palace Hotel, subsequently rebuilt, which had many famous visitors including royalty and celebrated performers.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was constructed in 1875 primarily financed by Bank of California co-founder William Ralston, the "man who built San Francisco".
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1906, the tenor Enrico Caruso and members of the Metropolitan Opera Company came to San Francisco to give a series of performances at the Grand Opera House.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The night after Caruso's performance in *Carmen*, the tenor was awakened in the early morning in his Palace Hotel suite by a strong jolt.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Clutching an autographed photo of President Theodore Roosevelt, Caruso made an effort to get out of the city, first by boat and then by train, and vowed never to return.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Metropolitan Opera Company lost all of its traveling sets and costumes.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the greatest losses from fire were in scientific laboratories.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Alice Eastwood, the curator of botany at the California Academy of Sciences in San Francisco, is credited with saving the entire plant type specimen collection of the Academy before the remainder of the largest botanical collection in the western United States was destroyed in the fire.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The entire laboratory and all the records of Benjamin R.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Jacobs, a biochemist who was researching the nutrition of everyday foods, were destroyed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The original California flag used in the 1846 Bear Flag Revolt at Sonoma, stored in a state building in San Francisco, was also destroyed in the fire.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, was gravely injured when the earthquake first struck and later died from his injuries.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan and his wife had been sleeping in the engine house adjoining the California Hotel on Bush Street when bricks crashed through the roof.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The interim fire chief sent an urgent request to the Presidio for dynamite.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] General Frederick Funston had already decided that the situation required the use of federal troops.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Telephoning a San Francisco Police Department officer, he sent word to Mayor Eugene Schmitz of his decision to assist and then ordered federal troops from nearby Angel Island to mobilize and enter the city.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Explosives were ferried across the bay from the California Powder Works in what is now Hercules.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days, soldiers provided valuable services like patrolling streets to discourage looting and guarding buildings such as the U.S.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They aided the fire department in dynamiting to demolish buildings in the path of the fires.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army also became responsible for feeding, sheltering, and clothing the tens of thousands of displaced residents of the city.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Under the command of Funston's superior, Major General Adolphus Greely, Commanding Officer of the Pacific Division, over 4,000 federal troops saw service during the emergency.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Police officers, firefighters, and soldiers would regularly commandeer passing civilians for work details to remove rubble and assist in rescues.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] On July 1, 1906, non-military authorities assumed responsibility for relief efforts, and the Army withdrew from the city.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accusations of soldiers engaging in looting also surfaced.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Retired Captain Edward Ord of the 22nd Infantry Regiment was appointed a special police officer by Schmitz and liaised with Greely for relief work with the 22nd Infantry and other military units involved in the emergency.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Ord later wrote a long letter to his mother on April 20 regarding Schmitz's "Shoot-to-Kill" order and some "despicable" behavior of certain soldiers of the 22nd Infantry who were looting.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He also made it clear that the majority of soldiers served the community well.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Property losses from the disaster have been estimated to be more than $400 million in 1906 dollars.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This is equivalent to $10.4 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An insurance industry source tallies insured losses at $235 million, the equivalent to $6.13 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Political and business leaders strongly downplayed the effects of the earthquake, fearing loss of outside investment in the city which was badly needed to rebuild.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake is not even mentioned in the statement.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fatality and monetary damage estimates were manipulated.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Almost immediately after the quake (and even during the disaster), planning and reconstruction plans were hatched to quickly rebuild the city.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rebuilding funds were immediately tied up by the fact that virtually all the major banks had been sites of the conflagration, requiring a lengthy wait of seven to ten days before their fire-proof vaults could cool sufficiently to be safely opened.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Bank of Italy (now Bank of America) had evacuated its funds and was able to provide liquidity in the immediate aftermath.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its president also immediately chartered and financed the sending of two ships to return with shiploads of lumber from Washington and Oregon mills which provided the initial reconstruction materials and surge.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Branner, who was the first to begin study of the San Andreas fault in 1891 complained that the Federal Government of the United States had not conducted the serious studies that were needed to gather data about earthquakes on the west coast.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He said public discussion was being stifled by fears that acknowledgement of earthquakes would drive away business and investors, and that geologists were told not to gather information about the 1906 earthquake, and certainly to not publish it.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some people went as far as to deny that an earthquake had happened.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven days after the earthquake a rare Sunday baseball game was played in New York City (which would not allow regular Sunday baseball until 1919) between the Highlanders (soon to be the Yankees) and the Philadelphia Athletics to raise money for quake survivors.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William James, the pioneering American psychologist, was teaching at Stanford at the time of the earthquake and traveled into San Francisco to observe first-hand its aftermath.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He was most impressed by the positive attitude of the survivors and the speed with which they improvised services and created order out of chaos.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This formed the basis of the chapter "On some Mental Effects of the Earthquake" in his book *Memories and Studies*.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Wells had just arrived in New York on his first visit to America when he learned of the San Francisco earthquake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] What struck him about the reaction of those around him was that "it does not seem to have affected any one with a sense of final destruction, with any foreboding of irreparable disaster.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Every one is talking of it this afternoon, and no one is in the least degree dismayed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] I have talked and listened in two clubs, watched people in cars and in the street, and one man is glad that Chinatown will be cleared out for good; another's chief solicitude is for Millet's *Man with a Hoe*.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'They'll cut it out of the frame,' he says, a little anxiously.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'Sure.' But there is no doubt anywhere that San Francisco can be rebuilt, larger, better, and soon.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Just as there would be none at all if all this New York that has so obsessed me with its limitless bigness was itself a blazing ruin.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was crucial in the development of the University of California, San Francisco and its medical facilities.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1906, the school faculty had provided care at the City-County Hospital (now the San Francisco General Hospital), but did not have a hospital of its own.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Following the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, more than 40,000 people were relocated to a makeshift tent city in Golden Gate Park and were treated by the faculty of the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This brought the school, which until then was located on the western outskirts of the city, in contact with significant population and fueled the commitment of the school towards civic responsibility and health care, increasing the momentum towards the construction of its own health facilities.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1907, one of the buildings was renovated for outpatient care with 75 beds.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This created the need to train nursing students, and the UC Training School for Nurses was established, adding a fourth professional school to the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The grandeur of citywide reconstruction schemes required investment from Eastern monetary sources, hence the spin and de-emphasis of the earthquake, the promulgation of the tough new building codes, and subsequent reputation sensitive actions such as the official low death toll.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the more famous and ambitious plans came from famed urban planner Daniel Burnham.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But this plan was dismissed during the aftermath of the earthquake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For example, real estate investors and other land owners were against the idea because of the large amount of land the city would have to purchase to realize such proposals.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Limestone used to reconstruct city buildings was quarried at the nearby Rockaway Quarry.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] City fathers likewise attempted at the time to eliminate the Chinese population and export Chinatown (and other poor populations) to the edge of the county where the Chinese could still contribute to the local taxbase.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Chinese occupants had other ideas and prevailed instead.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Chinatown was rebuilt in the newer, modern, Western form that exists today.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The destruction of City Hall and the Hall of Records enabled thousands of Chinese immigrants to claim residency and citizenship, creating a backdoor to the Chinese Exclusion Act, and bring in their relatives from China.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was also responsible for the development of the Pacific Heights neighborhood.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The immense power of the earthquake had destroyed almost all of the mansions on Nob Hill except for the James C.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others that had not been destroyed were dynamited by the Army forces aiding the firefighting efforts in attempts to create firebreaks.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As one indirect result, the wealthy looked westward where the land was cheap and relatively undeveloped, and where there were better views.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Constructing new mansions without reclaiming and clearing rubble simply sped attaining new homes in the tent city during the reconstruction.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Reconstruction was swift, and largely completed by 1915, in time for the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition which celebrated the reconstruction of the city and its "rise from the ashes".
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Since 1915, the city has officially commemorated the disaster each year by gathering the remaining survivors at Lotta's Fountain, a fountain in the city's financial district that served as a meeting point during the disaster for people to look for loved ones and exchange information.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army built 5,610 redwood and fir "relief houses" to accommodate 20,000 displaced people.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The houses were designed by John McLaren, and were grouped in 11 camps, packed close to each other and rented to people for two dollars per month until rebuilding was completed.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They were painted navy blue, partly to blend in with the site and partly because the military had large quantities of navy blue paint on hand.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps had a peak population of 16,448 people, but by 1907 most people had moved out.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps were then re-used as garages, storage spaces or shops.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The cottages cost on average $100 to build.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The $2 monthly rents went towards the full purchase price of $50.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The last official refugee camp was closed on June 30, 1908.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the cottages have been destroyed, but at least 30 survived.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Of the remaining structures, there is a historically restored pair in the Presidio.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others have been built on as part of private homes, with a high concentration around the Bernal Heights neighborhood.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the modest 720 sq ft (67 m2) homes was purchased in 2006 for more than $600,000.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A 2017 study found that the fire had the effect of increasing the share of land used for nonresidential purposes: "Overall, relative to unburned blocks, residential land shares on burned blocks fell while nonresidential land shares rose by 1931.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The study also provides insight into what held the city back from making these changes before 1906: the presence of old residential buildings.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In reconstruction, developers built relatively fewer of these buildings, and the majority of the reduction came through single-family houses.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Aside from merely expanding nonresidential uses in many neighborhoods, the fire created economic opportunities in new areas, resulting in clusters of business activity that emerged only in the wake of the disaster.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days after news of the disaster reached the rest of the world, relief efforts reached over $5,000,000, equivalent to $179,170,000 in 2025.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] London raised hundreds of thousands of dollars.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Individual citizens and businesses donated large sums of money for the relief effort: Standard Oil and Andrew Carnegie each gave $100,000; the Parliament of Canada made a special appropriation of $100,000; and even the Bank of Canada in Ottawa gave $25,000.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The United States Congress quickly appropriated 2.5 million dollars for relief supplies which were immediately rushed to the area, including supplies for food kitchens and many thousands of tents that city dwellers would occupy the next several years.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These relief efforts were not enough to get families on their feet again, and consequently the burden was placed on wealthier members of the city, who were reluctant to assist in the rebuilding of homes they were not responsible for.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] All residents were eligible for daily meals served from a number of communal soup kitchens, and citizens as far away as Idaho and Utah were known to send daily loaves of bread to San Francisco as relief supplies were coordinated by the railroads.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies, faced with staggering claims of $250 million, paid out between $235 million and $265 million on policyholders' claims, often for fire damage only, since shake damage from earthquakes was excluded from coverage under most policies.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At least 137 insurance companies were directly involved and another 17 as reinsurers.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Lloyd's of London reports having paid all claims in full, more than $50 million, thanks to the leadership of Cuthbert Heath.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies in Hartford, Connecticut, report paying every claim in full, with the Hartford Fire Insurance Company paying over $11 million and Aetna Insurance Company almost $3 million.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The insurance payments heavily affected the international financial system.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Gold transfers from European insurance companies to policyholders in San Francisco led to a rise in interest rates, subsequently to a lack of available loans and finally to the Knickerbocker Trust Company crisis of October 1907 which led to the Panic of 1907.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the 1906 earthquake, global discussion arose concerning a legally flawless exclusion of the earthquake hazard from fire insurance contracts.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was pressed ahead mainly by re-insurers.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Their aim: a uniform solution to insurance payouts resulting from fires caused by earthquakes.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1910, a few countries, especially in Europe, followed the call for an exclusion of the earthquake hazard from all fire insurance contracts.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the U.S., the question was discussed differently.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But the traumatized public reacted with fierce opposition.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the second half of 1909, the California State Legislature enacted the California Standard Form of Fire Insurance Policy, which did not contain any earthquake clause.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Thus the state decided that insurers would have to pay again if another earthquake was followed by fires.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Other earthquake-endangered countries followed the California example.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 Centennial Alliance was set up as a clearing-house for various centennial events commemorating the earthquake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Award presentations, religious services, a National Geographic TV movie, a projection of fire onto the Coit Tower, memorials, and lectures were part of the commemorations.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The USGS Earthquake Hazards Program issued a series of Internet documents, and the tourism industry promoted the 100th anniversary as well.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven survivors of the 1906 earthquake attended the centennial commemorations in 2006, including Irma Mae Weule (1899–2008), who was the oldest survivor of the quake at the time of her death in August 2008, aged 109.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Vivian Illing (1900–2009) was believed to be the second-oldest survivor at the time of her death, aged 108, leaving Herbert Hamrol (1903–2009) as the last known remaining survivor at the time of his death, aged 106.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another survivor, Libera Armstrong (1902–2007), attended the 2006 anniversary but died in 2007, aged 105.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shortly after Hamrol's death, two additional survivors were discovered.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte, then 103, and Jeanette Scola Trapani (1902–2009), 106, stated that they stopped attending events commemorating the earthquake when it became too much trouble for them.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte and another survivor, Rose Cliver (1902–2012), then 106, attended the earthquake reunion celebration on April 18, 2009, the 103rd anniversary of the earthquake.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nancy Stoner Sage (1905–2010) died, aged 105, in Colorado just three days short of the 104th anniversary of the earthquake on April 18, 2010.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte attended the event at Lotta's Fountain in 2010.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte (1906–2016), who died 11 days shy of his 110th birthday, was thought to be the last survivor.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005 the National Film Registry added *San Francisco Earthquake and Fire, April 18, 1906*, a newsreel documentary made soon after the earthquake, to its list of American films worthy of preservation.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Worden's gelatin silver prints documenting the destruction were later collected by the Museum of Modern Art in New York, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, and the Oakland Museum of California.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the destruction, all that remained of the Alban N.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Towne mansion on Nob Hill were six marble columns and a lintel.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] When viewed from a certain angle, the empty porch perfectly framed the ruins of the smoldering City Hall.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The haunting image became an icon of the 1906 earthquake, due largely to photographs by Worden.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 1909, the columns and lintel were relocated to Golden Gate Park, where, known as Portals of the Past, they became an enduring monument to the city's grief and a symbol of its endurance.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Copyright, Pillsbury Pictures, 18 April 1906.
[src:chester-stock/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its wood interior burned, but its steel, concrete and stone frame survived.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:chester-stock/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:chester-stock/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:chester-stock/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:chester-stock/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:chester-stock/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:chester-stock/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:chester-stock/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:chester-stock/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:chester-stock/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] Stock was born in San Francisco to John Englebert Stock and Maria Henriette Meyer, both German immigrants.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He grew up in a poor neighborhood, selling newspapers to earn some money.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He was educated at Starr King Primary School and Franklin Grammar School, spending weekends at a *Gymnasium* studying German, and learned to play tuba at a local Lutheran church.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He also took an interest in science, attending the annual mechanics fair and the museum of the California Academy of Sciences.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] His family home was destroyed by fires caused by the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, after which he joined the California National Guard.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He was forced by circumstances to leave school and seek employment in the Union Iron Works, at which time his health declined, and he came down with malaria.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] His mother and brother pushed him back into his studies, and he graduated in 1910 from Mission High School.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He then attended the University of California, Berkeley with the intent to study medicine, but influenced by John C.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] Merriam, instead took an interest in paleontology.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He authored a paper of the remains of the Rancho La Brea for his graduation in 1914, after which he continued his studies under Merriam.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He collected paleontological samples in the Hawker Cave for his 1918 PhD dissertation.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] He soon joined the university as an instructor, and when Merriam moved to Washington in 1921, began teaching vertebrate paleontology.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] The newly founded California Institute of Technology was being expanded by R.A.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] Buwalda and Chester Stock for the geology department.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] The plesiosaur *Morenosaurus stocki*, a flamingo *Phoenicopterus stocki*, and a fossil bat *Desmodus stocki* are among the species that have been named after him.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] In 1921, Chester married Clara Margaret Doud, with whom he had a son and a daughter.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] After her death in 1934, he married Margaret Gardner Wood in 1935, and they had another son.
[src:chester-stock/chester-stock] Stock was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1941, the American Philosophical Society in 1946, and the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1948.
